```tactics
/-Theorem: The length of a context-free derivation in chomsky normal-form
  is two times the length of the result word minus 1.-/
theorem CNF_derivation_lengths {α nt : Type} :
  ∀ cfgCNF : @ContextFreeGrammarCNF α nt, ∀ word : Word cfgCNF.val.Z,
  (word ∈ cfgCNF.val.GeneratedLanguage →
  (∀ derivation : (ContextFreeGrammar.ContextFreeDerivation cfgCNF.val (Word.mk [Sum.inl cfgCNF.val.start]) word.ZtoVZ),
  (2 * word.len) - 1 = derivation.length)) := by sorry
```

This lemma is a key property of derivations in Chomsky normal form. The length of the derivation is indeed $2 \cdot |w| - 1$ for a word $w$ in the language. This is because each step in the derivation corresponds to a production rule, and in Chomsky normal form, each rule either introduces a terminal or a pair of variables. So the length of the derivation is related to the number of symbols in the word.

